rComments: Prof. O'Toole specifically takes on a de-colonial teaching pedagogy for a de-colonial subject. This is not a class about lectures, but about participation. Our class suffered because no one wanted to participate and so Prof. O'Toole would have to lecture on the spot. He's extremely easy-going and understanding and people took advantage of that.

I feel bad but I given the criteria we are working with on this site the grade is accurate. O'Toole is very disorganized and unclear. Class is an Ojibwe language class and he purposefully steers away from other topics. The class was fun when we got to discuss tho! Otherwise, it was very uncomfortable. Readings carried the class.

Took his thematic course - Indigenous Legal Principles & was disappointed with how disorganized the class was. It was mostly readings & class discussion & I found it hard competing for "talk time" with certain students. He couldn't mediate the discussion & often I checked out. Loved learning Ojibwe though!
He was a good professor.  The class was not very well organized but that was not his fault though.
